            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>What are Light’s criteria?</h2>
              <p>
                Light’s criteria are a set of biochemical thresholds used to
                distinguish
                <strong>exudative</strong> from
                <strong>transudative</strong> pleural effusions. They combine
                pleural and serum protein and LDH values to identify exudates
                with high sensitivity.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  An effusion is classified as <strong>exudative</strong> if
                  <em>any</em> of the following are true:
                </p>
                <ol class="list-decimal ml-5">
                  <li>Pleural fluid protein / Serum protein &gt; 0.5</li>
                  <li>Pleural fluid LDH / Serum LDH &gt; 0.6</li>
                  <li>
                    Pleural fluid LDH &gt; 2/3 × upper limit of normal (ULN)
                    serum LDH
                  </li>
                </ol>
                <p class="mt-2 text-gray-600">
                  If <em>none</em> of the criteria are met, the effusion is
                  classified as <strong>transudative</strong>.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>How this calculator works</h3>
              <p>This tool:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Accepts protein in either g/dL or g/L (internally converted to
                  g/dL).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Calculates:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Pleural/serum protein ratio</li>
                    <li>Pleural/serum LDH ratio</li>
                    <li>2/3 × ULN serum LDH and compares it to pleural LDH</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Flags each criterion as <strong>positive</strong> or
                  <strong>negative</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Provides an overall classification (exudate vs transudate) and
                  a brief clinical note.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Interpreting the result</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Exudative effusion</strong> (one or more criteria
                  positive) is commonly due to: pneumonia, malignancy, pulmonary
                  embolism, tuberculosis, inflammatory or autoimmune disease,
                  pancreatitis, post–cardiac injury, etc.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Transudative effusion</strong> (all criteria negative)
                  is more often associated with: heart failure, cirrhosis with
                  ascites, nephrotic syndrome, hypoalbuminemia, or other
                  systemic causes of fluid overload.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Light’s criteria are highly sensitive for exudates but can
                misclassify some transudates (for example, in patients on
                diuretics). Always interpret results in the context of the
                clinical picture and imaging.
              </p>

              <h3>Limitations and caveats</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Borderline values near the cut-offs may be affected by lab
                  variability.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Diuretic therapy can concentrate pleural fluid and make a
                  transudate appear exudative.
                </li>
                <li>
                  In suspected heart failure with “exudative” Light’s criteria,
                  consider:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      Serum–pleural albumin gradient (&gt; 1.2 g/dL suggests
                      transudate)
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      Serum–pleural protein gradient (&gt; 3.1 g/dL suggests
                      transudate)
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Additional pleural fluid tests (pH, glucose, cell count,
                  cytology, microbiology) are often needed.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Frequently asked questions</h3>
              <h4>
                Can I use Light’s criteria if I only have some of the values?
              </h4>
              <p>
                You need at least one complete pair (pleural and serum) of
                protein or LDH values to apply the corresponding criterion. This
                calculator will still work with partial data but will indicate
                which criteria could not be evaluated.
              </p>

              <h4>Do I have to enter the ULN for serum LDH?</h4>
              <p>
                Yes, for the third criterion. The upper limit of normal varies
                by laboratory and assay. If you do not know it, you can omit
                that field; the calculator will still apply the first two
                criteria.
              </p>

              <h4>
                Is this calculator validated for clinical decision-making?
              </h4>
              <p>
                The underlying Light’s criteria are well validated in the
                literature, but this online implementation is provided for
                support and education only. It should not be used as the sole
                basis for diagnosis or management.
              </p>

              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-6">
                Disclaimer: This calculator does not provide medical advice,
                diagnosis, or treatment. Always confirm results with your local
                laboratory values and institutional guidelines, and consult a
                qualified clinician or pulmonologist when in doubt.
              </p>
